If you use Spring transaction, you can use a `TransactionSynchronization` for this kind of things. For example :

    TransactionSynchronizationManager.registerSynchronization(new TransactionSynchronization(){
               void afterCommit() {
                    ..
               }
    });

See [TransactionSynchronizationManager][1]


  [1]: http://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/transaction/support/TransactionSynchronizationManager.html

Hibernate 5 removed the ability to detect rollback in it&#39;s interceptor.  Instead one can capture that transaction was rolled back and infer a rollback if it was not committed.

For example:

    public class MyInterceptor extends EmptyInterceptor {
    .
    .
    .

    private static ThreadLocal&lt;Boolean&gt; wasCommited = new ThreadLocal();

    @Override
    public void beforeTransactionCompletion(Transaction tx) {
        // not called for rollback
        wasCommited.set(Boolean.TRUE);
    }


    @Override
    public void afterTransactionCompletion(Transaction tx) {

        if ( !Boolean.TRUE.equals(wasCommited.get()) ) {
            try {
               // handle transaction rolled back
            }
            finally {
                wasCommited.set(null);
            }
        }
    }
    }

I successfully utilized [`javax.transaction.Synchronization`][1] which can be registered with the transaction and receives correct status. It can be registered using the Hibernate Interceptor:

      @Override
      public void afterTransactionBegin(Transaction tx) {
        tx.registerSynchronization(new Synchronization() {
          @Override
          public void afterCompletion(int status) {
            // Here the status is correct
          }
        });
      }


-------------------------------------
**Edit:**

Unfortunattely, this solution works only, if the commit or rollback succeedes, otherwise the callback is not called. I must have had wrong test initially. You can see that in the code of `JdbcResourceLocalTransactionCoordinatorImpl.TransactionDriverControlImpl`.

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javaee/7/api/javax/transaction/Synchronization.html

After some struggle I ended up with [vnov&#39;s answer][1] to the Hibernate 5 solution (to replace the now missing &lt;code&gt;org.hibernate.Transaction.wsComitted()&lt;/code&gt; method). This answer elaborates more in depth on the problem solution. I am using &lt;code&gt;org.hibernate.EmptyInterceptor&lt;/code&gt; via Spring AOP.

&lt;pre&gt;
  @Before(&quot;bean(emptyInterceptor)
      &amp;&amp; execution(public * *.afterTransactionBegin(..))
      &amp;&amp; args(tx)&quot;)
  protected void afterTransactionBegin(org.hibernate.Transaction tx) {
    tx.registerSynchronization(new javax.transaction.Synchronization() {
      @Override
      public void beforeCompletion() {
      }
      @Override
      public void afterCompletion(int status) {
        /*
          status is e.g. javax.transaction.Status.STATUS_COMMITTED
          do my stuff here,
          i.e. move here the body of the
          afterTransactionCompletion(Transaction) method
        */
      }
    });
  }
&lt;/pre&gt;

In the 
&lt;code&gt;JdbcResourceLocalTransactionCoordinatorImpl.TransactionDriverControlImpl&lt;/code&gt; class source I see that:

 - If the commit fails, the RuntimeException will be caught and the transaction will be rolled back. So the &lt;code&gt;Synchronization.afterCompletion(int)&lt;/code&gt; method will then be called with the &lt;code&gt;status == Status.STATUS_UNKNOWN&lt;/code&gt; in case of a successful rollback.
 - &lt;b&gt;If the rollback fails with an exception, the &lt;code&gt;Synchronization.afterCompletion(int)&lt;/code&gt; method will not be called at all.&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;b&gt;Edit (2021-11-24)&lt;/b&gt;

As we needed a solution that also considers possibility of the rollback failure, we came up with this solution (the &lt;code&gt;afterTransactionCompletion&lt;/code&gt; method is called also after the rollback failed).

&lt;pre&gt;
  private ThreadLocal&amp;lt;Boolean&gt; txCommitted = ThreadLocal.withInitial(() -&gt; false);

  @Before(&quot;bean(emptyInterceptor)
      &amp;&amp; execution(public * *.afterTransactionBegin(..))
      &amp;&amp; args(tx)&quot;)
  protected void afterTransactionBegin(org.hibernate.Transaction tx) {
    tx.registerSynchronization(new Synchronization() {
      @Override
      public void beforeCompletion() {
      }
      @Override
      public void afterCompletion(int status) {
        txCommitted.set(status == Status.STATUS_COMMITTED);
      }
    });
  }

  @Before(&quot;bean(emptyInterceptor)
      &amp;&amp; execution(public * *.afterTransactionCompletion(..))
      &amp;&amp; args(tx)&quot;)
  protected void afterTransactionCompletion(org.hibernate.Transaction tx) {
    if (txCommitted.get()) {
      /* do my on-commit stuff here */
    } else {
      /* do my otherwise stuff here */
    }
  }
&lt;/pre&gt;

  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/37523461/302517

